231010_create_L2_dataset

2023-10-10

Goal

The goal of this script works off of L1 data, which has been imported from GDrive and reformatted into a format thats convenient for our analysis needs, but hasnt been otherwise processed. The script will take L1 data and convert it to L2 data, which will include percent change calculations. This is a small and supposedly simple step, but since its been the source of a lot of uncertainty, were going to take a full script to do the calculations, verify theyre doing what we expect, and confirm stats for Figure 3 etc make sense prior to exporting.

Expectations for percentages

Based on the figures above, and using the agreed-upon formula of percent_change = (fire - baseline) / baseline) x 100, we would expect percent changes on the order of - Flow: max of ~ 20% - Sediment: max of ~ 2% - NO3: max of ~ 170% - DOC: max of ~ 625%

So lets try calculating values, and see what we get. It is important to note that im calculating percents based on data thats already been summarized to means, not the raw data:

Check binned percent plots

These all look as expected, and dont explain why we had a disconnect between absolute and percent calculations in the original L1 dataset. Lets calculate percents for the full dataset, then bin, then plot, and see if that replicates the issue:

Check percent plots

Flow

Sediment

NO3

DOC

AHA - thats the issue!

So, when we calculate means FIRST then calculate percent change SECOND, we get sensible values. When we calculate percent change FIRST for every date, then calculate means SECOND, it over-inflates changes in NO3 and DOC (likely influence of outliers). As such, L2 is going to be the dataset, but calculating means first, then percent changes second to feed proper data to Figure 3 and beyond.
